R Tutorial Code

Julia Arenson

Introduction

R is a powerful and flexible program that scientists use to analyze and visualize their data. This tutorial is an introduction to the basics of the R language, and to some of the graphing options to you through R.

Basic equations in R

1 + 1 
2 * 4
8 / 2
x <- 5
y <- 81
x + y
5 + 81
science <- "fun"

Functions in R

The basic format for using functions in R is:

function(arguments)
help(mean)
mean(x, y)
mean(c(x, y))

Getting some data in

iris <- iris

Looking at your data

unique(iris$Species)
mean(iris[,3])
iris[3,2]
iris[1:4,] 
iris[,c(1,3)]
mean(iris$Petal.Length)

Additional functions include:

Minimum: min()

Maximum: max()

Standard deviation: sd()

Median: median()

min(iris[,"Sepal.Width"])
colMeans(iris[,c("Sepal.Length", "Petal.Width")])
colMeans(iris[,c(1,4)])

Plotting in R

plot(Petal.Length ~ Petal.Width, data = iris)

plot(Petal.Length ~ Petal.Width, data = iris, col = Species)

plot(Petal.Length ~ Petal.Width, data = iris, col = Species)
legend(2, 2, unique(iris$Species), col = 1:length(iris$Species), pch = 1)

plot(Petal.Length ~ Petal.Width, data = iris, col = Species,
     main = "Petal Dimensions", xlab = "Petal Width", ylab = "Petal Length")
legend(2, 2, unique(iris$Species), col = 1:length(iris$Species), pch = 1)

hist(iris$Sepal.Length)

boxplot(Sepal.Width ~ Species, data = iris)

gg-plotting

install.packages("ggplot2")
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(dataset, aes(x, y)) + layers

ggplot(iris, aes(Petal.Length, Petal.Width)) + 
  geom_point()

ggplot(iris, aes(Petal.Length, Petal.Width)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = Species))

ggplot(iris, aes(Petal.Length, Petal.Width)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = Species, shape = Species))

?pch
ggplot(iris, aes(Petal.Length, Petal.Width)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = Species), shape = 12)

ggplot(iris, aes(Petal.Length, Petal.Width)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = Species)) + 
  geom_smooth(method="lm", se=FALSE, color = "black")

ggplot(iris, aes(Species, Petal.Length)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = Species))

ggplot(iris, aes(Species, Petal.Length)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = Species)) + 
  labs(title = "Petal Length by Species", 
       x = "Variety", y = "Length of Petal", 
       fill = "Variety")

ggplot(iris, aes(Species, Petal.Length)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = Species)) + 
  labs(title = "Petal Length by Species", 
       x = "Variety", y = "Length of Petal", 
       fill = "Variety") +
  theme_classic(15)

RColorBrewer::display.brewer.all()

ggplot(iris, aes(Species, Petal.Length)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = Species)) + 
  labs(title = "Petal Length by Species", x = "Variety", y = "Length of Petal", 
       fill = "Variety") +
  theme_classic(15) + 
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Accent")

Colors in R

colors <- c("firebrick2", "darkorchid1", "goldenrod1")

ggplot(iris, aes(Species, Petal.Length)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = Species)) + 
  labs(title = "Petal Length by Species", x = "Variety", y = "Length of Petal", 
       fill = "Variety") +
  theme_classic(15) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = colors)

help.search("geom_", package = "ggplot2")

More datasets

Explore additional datasets available through R:

data()

Some good ones through base R include the Tree, Loblolly, and beaver1 datasets (look at their documentation with the command we learned earlier). ggplot2 also has some datasets you can play around with- mpg has data on several car makes, and diamonds has prices and other attributes of diamonds.
